    "For example, a scientist who wishes to validate a hypothesis might only be interested in the impact of one concept (e.g., how tone impacts the popularity of social media content (Tan et al., 2014)).",
    "The idea of not providing a complete explanation is also grounded in the philosophy, psychology, and cognitive science literature.",
    "For instance, Miller (2017) advocates that explanations can be selective (humans select a few salient causes instead of a complete causal chain when explaining) and contrastive (Explanations should answer Why P of Q? rather than Why P?",
